                    <div class="modal-body">
              
                        <p>Although it is a region of Italy, Sicily is very different from its mother country, in part because of its storied past. The island was first inhabited 10,000 years ago by people from the Iberian Peninsula. Over the centuries, it was occupied, settled or conquered by a dozen or more ethnic groups including the Greeks, Romans, Byzantines, Arabs, Normans and Bourbons&mdash;and remnants of these diverse cultures can be found both in the island&rsquo;s archaeological ruins and in its unique character. In the 19<sup>th</sup> century, Sicily was a major center of revolutionary movements and finally, in 1861, it was incorporated into the Kingdom of Italy. In 1947, Sicily gained regional autonomy. Today, many locals consider themselves Sicilian rather than Italian.</p>
                        <p>More than four-fifths of Sicily is covered with hills and mountains. Towering above them all is <a href="http://www.visitsicily.info/en/il-monte-etna-2/">Mount Etna</a>, which, at 10,900 feet, is Europe&rsquo;s highest volcano and one of the most active in the world. Mount Etna has spewed lava and ash for about 500,000 years and continues to fascinate scientists and visitors with its frequent fiery fountains and lava flows. In contrast to the mountain&rsquo;s lunar landscape of black sand and volcanic rocks are the fertile plains and golden beaches of Catania just a few miles away.</p>
