        <div class="modal fade" id="mytaorminamodal" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="myModalLabel">
            <div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
                <div class="modal-content">
                    <div class="modal-header">

                        <h4 class="modal-title" id="myModalLabel">About Taormina</h4>
                        <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close"><span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span></button>
                    </div>
                    <div class="modal-body">
                       
                        <p>Taormina&rsquo;s perfect panoramas of the Ionian Sea, rocky hillsides and Mount Etna in the distance have inspired novelists and writers over the centuries. In the late 1700s, the German writer Goethe praised Taormina in his book, "Italian Journey," to such a degree that it became an integral part of the Grand Tour, which was taken by fashionable English gentlemen and intellectuals for education and refinement. This newfound international popularity established Taormina as an idyllic tourist destination, a reputation it enjoys to this day. Visitors come from all over the world to see the famous <a href="http://www.visitsicily.info/en/il-teatro-greco-di-taormina/">Teatro Greco</a> (Greek theater), amble along perfectly preserved medieval streets, admire dramatic views of Mount Etna and immerse themselves in Mediterranean atmosphere.</p>
                        <p>Taormina&rsquo;s main thoroughfare is Corso Umberto I, a lively promenade lined with elegant shops and restaurants. At each end of the street are gates, Porta Catania and Porta Messina, built in the city&rsquo;s ancient fortification walls. At the beginning of Corso Umberto I is <a href="https://www.traveltaormina.com/en/monuments/palazzo-corvaja-taormina.html">Palazzo Corvaja</a>, a medieval palace featuring a mix of Arab, Norman and Gothic architecture, battlements, mullioned windows and shady courtyards. Halfway down is the Clock Tower, which has been destroyed several times and always rebuilt. At the other end is Piazza del Duomo, a picturesque square with the 13<sup>th</sup>-century <a href="https://www.taormina.it/duomo-of-taormina">Cathedral of Taormina</a> and a Baroque fountain built in 1635. Other popular Taormina sights include the <a href="https://www.taormina.it/taormina-the-odeon">Odeon</a>, an ancient Roman theater; <a href="https://www.italyscapes.com/places/sicily/taormina/squares/piazza-ix-aprile/">Piazza IX Aprile</a>, the town&rsquo;s main square and arguably its most beautiful; and <a href="https://www.traveltaormina.com/en/beaches/isola-bella-taormina.html">Isola Bella</a>, a small island connected to Taormina by a thin strip of beach that disappears and reappears with the tides.</p>
                        <p>For shopping enthusiasts, Taormina offers everything from antiques and pottery to postcards and souvenirs. Corso Umberto I and the terraced alleys that meander from it showcase uniquely Sicilian treasures including Caltagirone ceramics, pottery, leather goods, jewelry and embroidery.</p>
                        <p>A <a href="https://www.traveltaormina.com/en/how-to-reach-us/cable-car.html">cable car</a> (&ldquo;funivia&rdquo; in Italian) connects the historic center of Taormina to the beach area of Mazzaro, where Belmond Villa Sant&rsquo;Andrea is located. Cable cars run every 15 minutes from 8:00 am &ndash; 1:00 am, Tuesday through Sunday; and from 9:00 am &ndash; 1:00 am on Monday. A one-way ticket is three euros, a day ticket is 10 euros and a weekly ticket for nonresidents is 50 euros. Most shops and restaurants in Taormina are within walking distance of the cable car station.</p>
